sentence: Disappointing corporate earnings coupled with a huge miss for December orders for durable goods fueled a near 400 point sell-off in the Dow Jones Industrial Average at Tuesday's open, leaving all three indices below their 50-day moving averages.

Stocks continue to trade close to 2% lower in midday trade despite better-than-expected home sales and a 7-year high in consumer confidence as Wall Street is unnerved by the damage to corporate earnings from the dollar's meteoric appreciation against other currencies.
Before the open, futures were already trading sharply lower on the back of an earnings miss from Microsoft ( MSFT ) and profit warning from Caterpillar ( CAT ).

DuPont ( DD ) saw its sales drop 5% in its latest quarter due to the loss of a competitive advantage as the dollar strengthened, while Procter & Gamble ( PG ) said it expects currency valuations to reduce its FY15 profit by 12%.
With many of the year-end 2014 earnings already coming in below expectations, today's results renewed doubts about future economic growth and corporate profits.
Economic data today was mixed and did little to overshadow an unexpected decline in durable goods orders of 3.4% versus estimates for a 0.7% gain.
In addition, November durable goods was revised downward to a 2.1% decline from the 0.7% drop initially reported.
Excluding transportation orders, durable goods were down 0.8%, missing estimates for a 0.8% gain.
Also today, the Case-Shiller house seasonally-adjusted price index of housing prices in 20 metropolitan areas rose 0.7% in November, edging out estimates looking for a 0.6% rise.
The January flash Purchasing Manager's Index for the services industry improved to 54.0 from 53.3 (final) in December, better than expectations for an improvement to 53.8.
December new home sales jumped 11.4% to 481,000, beating forecasts for a 3.2% gain to 452,000.
For the month prior, home sales was revised downward to 431,000 from 438,000.
Manufacturing activity in the Mid-Atlantic region declined slightly as the Richmond Fed index fell back to 6.0 from 7.0 in December.
This is just above the estimated 5.5.
Finally, falling energy costs fueled a 7-year high in the consumer confidence index to 102.9, much greater than estimates for an increase in the index to 96.0 from December's revised 93.1.
European equities all closed lower as the fallout from the Greek election reverberates through EU-zone markets, and weak corporate earnings also contributes to today's heavy losses.
The UK's FTSE fared slightly better as year-over-year Q4 GDP was slightly better from 2013, but still shed 0.60% in sympathy with the rest of Europe.
Crude oil was up $1.00 to $46.15 per barrel.
Natural gas was up $0.10 to $2.95 per 1 million BTU.
Gold was up $11.10 to $1,290.40 an ounce, while silver was up $0.09 to $18.07 an ounce.
Copper was down $0.09 to $2.45 per pound.
Among energy ETFs, the United States Oil Fund was up 2.61% to $17.31 with the United States Natural Gas Fund was up 3.71% to $15.09.
Amongst precious-metal funds, the Market Vectors Gold Miners ETF was up 2.54 to 22.58 while SPDR Gold Shares were up 0.80% to $123.97.
The iShares Silver Trust was up 0.85% to $17.28.

Here's where the U.S. markets stood at mid-day:
